<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT OF NICHOLAS PERON</TI>
<P>I, NICHOLAS PERON, of the City of Ottawa, in the Province of Ontario, MAKE OATH AND SAY THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am an officer with the International Tax Services Office of the Canada Revenue Agency (the &ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) and made the decision to deny the applicant's request for an extension of time to file Ms 2010 Subsection 216(4) Income Tax Return (the &ldquo;S.216(4) Return&rdquo;) pursuant to subsections 216(4) and 220(3) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.), as amended (the &ldquo;<EM>Act</EM>&rdquo;). As such, I have personal knowledge of the matters deposed to, save and except what is stated to be on information and belief. Where I have referred in my affidavit to information obtained from specific sources, I believe that information to be true. Where I have referred in my affidavit to information without disclosing the source, the information was derived either from my first-hand knowledge or from my review of the CRA file for the applicant.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Failure to File Return: Notifications</UNDER></TI>
<P>2. By letter dated March 30, 2009, the CRA notified the applicant that he was considered a non-resident and may be subject to non-resident withholding tax on rental income received from a Canadian source. A true copy of this letter dated March 30, 2009 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;.</P>
<P>3. By letter dated January 21, 2010, the CRA informed the applicant that his submission for an &ldquo;Undertaking to File an Income Tax Return by a Non-Resident Receiving Rent from Real Property or Receiving a Timber Royalty&rdquo; for the 2010 taxation year (the &ldquo;NR6 Form&rdquo;) was incomplete and was being returned to him. A true copy of this letter dated January 21, 2010 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P>
<P>4. By letter dated February 9, 2010, the CRA acknowledged receipt of the Applicant's NR6 Form and deemed it to apply for the 2010 taxation year. A true copy of this letter dated February 9, 2010 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;.</P>
<P>5. By letter dated December 31, 2010 and received by the CRA on January 16, 2011, the applicant attempted to advise the CRA that he had returned to Canada and was no longer a non-resident by submitting the form &ldquo;Statement of Amounts Paid or Credited to Non-Residents of Canada&rdquo; (the &ldquo;NR4 Form&rdquo;). The applicant also indicated that he had attached a cheque in the amount of $180 and requested that his non-residency account be closed. A true copy of the letter dated December 31, 2010 and NR4 Form is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;.</P>
<P>6. On February 16, 2011, Horace Sailsman, who was acting as the applicant's representative (the &ldquo;Representative&rdquo;) telephoned the CRA to see if the NR4 Form was received and also asked to close the non-residency account once it was processed. An officer of the CRA advised the Representative that the CRA had received the NR4 Form but had not yet processed it A true copy of the Account Notes for Account XXXXXXXXXX is attached here to as Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;.</P>
<P>7. By letter dated September 26, 2011, the CRA advised the Representative that the applicant failed to file a S.216(4) Return as undertaken by his NR6 Form by the June 30, 2011 deadline. The CRA further advised the applicant that a 25% non-resident tax was thus payable. A true copy of this letter dated September 26, 2011 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;.</P>
<P>8. By letter dated October 9, 2011, the Representative advised the CRA that the applicant was not aware that he was required to file a S.216(4) Return for the 2010 taxation year as he had already filed a NR4 Form with a letter indicating that he had reclaimed residency status and had requested that the non-resident account be closed. The applicant also attached to the letter a S.216(4) Return. A true copy of this letter dated October 9, 2011 and S.216(4) Return is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;.</P>
<P>9. By letter dated February 2, 2012, the CRA acknowledged receiving the applicant's letter of October 9, 2011, and informed the applicant that the matter would be referred to the Taxpayer Relief Committee for consideration (the &ldquo;Request&rdquo;). A true copy of this letter dated February 2, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Taxpayer Relief Review Procedure&mdash;First Level</UNDER></TI>
<P>10. By letter dated March 1, 2012, the CRA informed the applicant that it had treated the applicant's letter of October 9, 2011 as a request for an extension of time to file a S.216(4) Return under subsection 220(3) of the <EM>Act</EM> (the &ldquo;First Request&rdquo;). The CRA further informed the applicant that it had sent the submission to the Taxpayer Relief Committee for consideration. A true copy of this letter dated March 1, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</P>
<P>11. Rajah Nithiya, a Taxpayer Relief Officer with the CRA, reviewed and considered the First Request As a result of the review, Mr. Nithiya recommended to deny the request for an extension of time to file and cancellation of the Part XIII assessment. Mr. Nithiya noted that the applicant was not a first time non-resident tax filer and had filed his 2009 non-resident return on time so should have been aware of the filing requirements for the 2010 taxation year. Further, Mr. Nithiya noted that the only reason given for the late filing was that the applicant misunderstood the process as he believed his letter requesting the non-resident account be closed would obviate the need to file a S.216(4) Return for the 2010 taxation year. However, Mr. Nithiya stated that negligence or carelessness do not validate circumstances that were beyond a taxpayer's control in meeting their filing requirement and thus recommended to deny the applicant's request. A true copy of the memorandum dated March 7, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;.</P>
<P>12. Mr, Nithiya's recommendation to deny relief was approved by Rhonda Pommainville, a Team Leader with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the memorandum dated March 7, 2012.</P>
<P>13. By letter dated March 12, 2012, the CRA advised the applicant of its decision to deny the request for extension of time to file and cancellation of the Part XIII assessment (the &ldquo;First Level Decision&rdquo;). A true copy of the First Level Decision is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Taxpayer Relief Review Procedure&mdash;Second Level</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. By fax dated March 28, 2012, the applicant applied to the Director of International Tax Services of the CRA for reconsideration of the CRA's decision to deny his request for extension of time to file his 2010 S.216(4) Return (the &ldquo;Second Request&rdquo;). This letter was treated as a request for an administrative review of the First Level Decision. A true copy of the Second Request dated March 28, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo;.</P>
<P>15. By letter dated April 16, 2012, the CRA advised the applicant that it had received the Second Request and had sent his submission to the Taxpayer Relief Committee for consideration. A true copy of the letter dated April 16, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;.</P>
<P>16. Beryl Hobbs, a Taxpayer Relief Officer of the International Tax Services Office of the CRA was assigned the task of reviewing the applicant's request for administrative review of the First Level Decision (the &ldquo;Second Level Decision&rdquo;).</P>
<P>17. During her review of the applicant's Second Request, Ms. Hobbs reviewed and considered the following:
<P1>(a) all records pertaining to the applicant available on the CRA's online computer system;</P1>
<P1>(b) all of the facts as represented by the applicant set out in the paragraphs above; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the applicant's submission that he was undergoing family difficulties, his representative is his father who was 79 years old, and that he believed submitting an NR4 form along with a cheque and letter notifying of his change in status would make him compliant with his S.216(4) obligations.</P1></P>
<P>18. Ms. Hobbs' analysis of the applicant's submission is contained in her report dated July 16, 2012 (the &ldquo;Second Level Report&rdquo;). A true copy of the Second Level Report as well as CRA computer printouts &ldquo;Account Notes&rdquo; and &ldquo;Tax Filing History&rdquo; is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;. In summary, she noted the following:
<P1>(a) it was not the applicant's first time for filing a S.216(4) Return as he had filed one for the 2009 taxation year on time;</P1>
<P1>(b) the applicant was notified by letter dated February 9, 2010 advising him of his filing requirements and the deadline of June 30, 2011; and</P1>
<P1>(c) there was no indication of any extraordinary circumstances which prevented the applicant from filing the required return for the 2010 taxation year on time.</P1></P>
<P>19. Based on the above, Ms. Hobbs therefore recommended that the Second Request be denied.</P>
<P>20. Ms. Hobbs' recommendation to deny relief was reviewed and recommended by the. following CRA officers:
<P1>(a) Dragan Milasin, a Team Leader with the CRA, as evidenced by his signature on the Second Level Report dated July 16, 2012;</P1>
<P1>(b) Elaine Whiteman, a Manager with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Second Level Report dated July 16, 2012;</P1>
<P1>(c) Adnan Khan, an Assistant Director with the CRA, as evidenced by his signature on the Second Level Report dated July 17, 2012;</P1>
<P1>(d) Kathleen Butler, an Assistant Director with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Second Level Report dated July 20, 2012; and</P1>
<P1>(e) Gillian Pranke, a Director with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Second Level Report dated July 24, 2012. The director had the ultimate signing authority and her word is final.</P1></P>
<P>21. By letter dated August 23, 2012, the CRA advised the applicant of its decision to deny the Second Request for relief (the &ldquo;Second Level Decision&rdquo;). A true copy of the Second Level Decision dated August 23, 2012 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo;.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Judicial Review of the Second Level Decision</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. On January 16, 2013, the applicant made an application to the Federal Court for a judicial review of the Second Level Decision.</P>
<P>23. On May 5, 2013, the applicant discontinued the application as the respondent agreed to refer the Request for reconsideration by another officer of the CRA not previously involved in the matter.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Taxpayer Relief Review Procedure&mdash;Third Level</UNDER></TI>
<P>24. I was assigned the task of reviewing the applicant's request for administrative review of the Second Level Decision (the &ldquo;Third Request&rdquo;).</P>
<P>25. During my review of the applicant's Request, I reviewed and considered, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the following:
<P1>(a) all records pertaining to the applicant available on the CRA's online computer system;</P1>
<P1>(b) all of the facts as represented by the applicant set out in the paragraphs above as well as the First Level Decision and Second Level Decision; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the applicant's submission that he was undergoing family difficulties, his representative is his father who was 79 years old, and that he believed submitting an NR4 form along with a cheque and letter notifying of his change in status would make him compliant with his S.216(4) obligations.</P1></P>
<P>26. My analysis of the applicant's submission is contained in my report dated June 17, 2013 (the &ldquo;Third Level Report&rdquo;). A true copy of the Third Level Report is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;P&rdquo;. In summary, I noted the following:
<P1>(a) the phone calls the Agent made to the CRA on February 16, 2011 as well as when the applicant returned to Canada in 2011 would not have prompted a CRA phone agent to advise him of the applicant's tax filing requirements unless he volunteered the information that he was collecting rental income as a non-resident. This is because a CRA phone agent would not know the requirements of each taxpayer's specific situation;</P1>
<P1>(b) the applicant not knowing his filing requirements is not a valid reason as per the Self-Assessment Policy;</P1>
<P1>(c) the applicant and his agent were advised of the filing requirement on the NR6 form and the approval letters issued to them when the NR6 was approved;</P1>
<P1>(d) in regards to the divorce and custody battle, the events outlined by the applicant all occurred in the 2010 tax year. He had returned to Canada in 2011 and the S.216(4) Return was due months after the events as described;</P1>
<P1>(e) the applicant stated that when he was in Canada he had to start all over and that his son was traumatized and he needed to focus on that but does not elaborate how this prevented him from filing; and</P1>
<P1>(f) despite the above claims, the applicant filed an immigrant/emigrant income tax return on May 17, 2011 which demonstrated that he was able to file a return during the period, two months prior to the due date for the S.216(4) Return. A true copy of the Income Tax Return filed on May 17, 2011 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>27. Based on the above, I therefore recommended that the Second Request be denied.</P>
<P>28. My recommendation to deny relief was reviewed and recommended by the following CRA officers:
<P1>(a) Derrick Ward, a Team Leader with the CRA, as evidenced by his signature on the Third Level Report dated June 28, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(b) Andrea Schieda for Elaine Whiteman, a Manager with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Third Level Report dated July 2, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(c) Krista Dease for John Paisley, an Assistant Director with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Third Level Report dated July 2, 2013;</P1>
<P1>(d) Brian Rae, an Assistant Director with the CRA, as evidenced by his signature on the Third Level Report dated July 3, 2013; and</P1>
<P1>(e) Gillian Pranke, a Director with the CRA, as evidenced by her signature on the Third Level Report. The director had the ultimate signing authority and her word is final.</P1></P>
<P>29. By letter dated July 23, 2013, the CRA advised the applicant of its decision to deny the Third Request for relief (the &ldquo;Third Level Decision&rdquo;). A true copy of the Third Level Decision dated July 23, 2013 is attached hereto as Exhibit &ldquo;R&rdquo;.</P>
<P>30. I make this affidavit in response to the applicant's application for judicial review of the CRA's Third Level Decision and for no other or improper purpose.</P>
